entry.definition: a continuous area or expanse which is free, available, or unoccupied

examples.text: a table took up much of the space
we shall all be living together in a small space
he reversed out of the parking space

entry.definition: the dimensions of height, depth, and width within which all things exist and move

examples.text: the work gives the sense of a journey in space and time

entry.definition: an interval of time (often used to suggest that the time is short considering what has happened or been achieved in it)

examples.text: both their cars were stolen in the space of three days

entry.definition: the portion of a text or document available or needed to write about a subject

examples.text: there is no space to give further details

entry.definition: the freedom to live, think, and develop in a way that suits one

examples.text: a teenager needing her own space

entry.definition: one of two possible states of a signal in certain systems.
position (two or more items) at a distance from one another
